ad | An essential part of gut health and hormone balancing is lowering your stress levels. 
High cortisol levels (the stress hormone) causes inflammation in the gut, raises blood sugar,
and throws your hormones all out of balance.

One of my most effective wellness habits for lowering stress has been having a wind down/evening routine. I recently started using the @lifeprousa Rejuvawrap X Infrared Sauna Blanket a few times a week before I shower and it helps give me a little reset between a busy day and a calm evening.

Benefits include:
- detoxification
- better sleep
- improved circulation
- reduced stress

If you want the benefits of sauna sessions without the expensive appointments and sweaty drives home, this is a great option! #lifepropartner #lifeprolaunch

My go to’s when I need a mental reset 🫶🏼

It’s no secret that I am grieving and how much it’s affected me. That has made it much more common for me to get into a bad headspace and need a complete reset. 

Most of the time I know which action will help most for that specific moment, but if you try a few and still don’t feel better - cry it out. Sometimes that’s what is needed, and that’s okay 🤍

And remember: you can restart your day at any time.

If you’re in need of a nourishing, gut healthy recipe that will make you glow from the inside out, you need to try this golden cauliflower soup 💛

balanced with fiber, protein and healthy fat and would be perfect for your luteal phase!

Recipe:
- 1 head of cauliflower
- 2 whole carrots or 1 cup baby carrots
- 1 shallot
- 3 garlic cloves
- 2 cups vegetable broth
- 1/2 cup lentils
- 1 cup non-dairy milk
- 1/2 cup coconut milk
- 1 tsp. turmeric
- 1 tsp. cumin
- 1/2 tsp sea salt
- 1/4 tsp black pepper

Instructions:
- preheat oven to 425°F. Slice cauliflower, carrots (if whole) and quarter the shallot.
- lay out on baking sheet and toss with olive oil and seasonings. roast for 30 minutes.
- while the veggie are roasting, boil your lentils and vegetable broth.
- add roasted veggies, lentils & broth, and coconut milk to a blender. blend until smooth. 

serve with warm sourdough & enjoy!

Eating in alignment with my cycle improved my intense, and often debilitating, PMS symptoms (if you still have painful periods, save this and start here!) along with lifestyle changes like anti-inflammatory foods & stress management. 

Cycle Syncing doesn’t need to be complicated — focus on a small handful of foods to prioritize for each phase, and do your best to stick with having warm foods in your luteal and menstrual phase. This doesn’t mean you can’t have a certain food in other phases, just that it’s something you want to prioritize getting plenty of in that phase! 🫶🏼 Here’s a simple guide to follow:

Menstruation
Days 1-6
‘Winter’

Hormone levels are low

Focus on:
Warming foods
Dark chocolate, chicken, turkey, tofu, eggs, avocado, sweet potato, squash, rice, bell peppers, berries.

Follicular
Days 7-14
‘Spring’

Estrogen is rising preparing for ovulation

Focus on:
Yogurt, berries, citrus, dark leafy greens, chickpeas, avocado, salmon.

Ovulatory
Days 15-17
‘Summer’

Estrogen & testosterone peak

Focus on:
Foods that support estrogen elimination 
Broccoli, Brussel sprouts, kale, cabbage, berries, citrus, dandelion tea.

Luteal
Days 18-28
‘Autumn’

Progesterone rises, metabolism speeds up

Focus on:
Warming foods as uterine lining builds
Sweet potato, turkey, dark leafy greens, red raspberry leaf tea, walnuts, almonds.

*every woman’s cycle varies – this is a general guide. Not medical advice.*
